-- 
CHILE DAYBOOK: Statistics Institute Releases April Inflation

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s
-- 
2011-05-06T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/chile-daybook-statistics-institute-releases-april-inflation.html
Consumer prices probably rose 0.4
percent in April from March, according to the median estimate of
economists surveyed by Bloomberg. The National Statistics
Institute releases data at 7 a.m. New York time.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Brewer Cia. Cervecerias Unidas SA holds a conference call to
discuss first-quarter earnings at 11 a.m. New York time.
*Salmon farmer Multiexport Foods SA may disclose first-quarter
earnings at a time to be advised.  ECONOMY:
* Chile ’s economy grew a record 15.2 percent in March from a year
earlier, when the country was recovering from an 8.8-magnitude
earthquake, the central bank said on its website. The median
forecast of 17 economists surveyed by Bloomberg was for the
gross domestic product proxy to rise 15 percent.
*Economic activity expanded 0.3 percent from the previous month
on a seasonally-adjusted basis on gains in the manufacturing,
retail, transport and aquaculture industries, the bank said.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index rose 0.6 percent to 4,788.84.
*Banco de Credito e Inversiones rose 3.4 percent to 31,339
pesos. Chile’s fourth-largest lender had its credit outlook
revised to “positive” from “stable” by  Standard & Poor’s .
*Cencosud SA fell 0.5 percent to 3,518.4 pesos.  Latin America ’s
third-largest retailer by sales said it “acted in good faith”
in sending tax-free donations from  Argentina  to Chile after a
February 2010 earthquake. Argentine authorities are
investigating whether the goods were sold in Chile instead of
donated, eluding tax payments.
*CFR Pharmaceuticals SA surged 13 percent to 96.36 pesos in its
trading debut. The family-owned  drug company  raised 173 billion
pesos in Chile’s first initial public offering this year.
*Empresas CMPC SA rose 1.4 percent to 25,200 pesos. Chile’s
second-largest pulp exporter reported first-quarter profit of
$141 million, up from $79.5 million a year earlier.
*Lan Airlines SA, Latin America’s largest airline by market
value, rose 3 percent to 13,190 pesos.  Oil prices  plunged,
signaling lower fuel costs for transport companies.  MARKETS:
*Chilean short-term inflation expectations jumped on speculation
the price of bread may rise in response to higher global food
prices even as plunging oil prices stemmed rises in longer-term
expectations. Three-month breakeven inflation gained 42 basis
points, or 0.42 percent point to 4.66 percent.
*Chile’s peso slid for a second day as the lowest copper prices
in six months signaled a diminished  trade surplus  for the
world’s biggest producer of the metal. The peso fell 0.6 percent
to 468.77 per  U.S. dollar .
*Foreign investors in the forwards market increased bets against
the Chilean peso to $1.9 billion on May 3 from $1.4 billion on
May 2, according to central bank data.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
